 Given the payoff structure, it seems like a dominant strategy game. If I always pick 'R', I would end up with more money in most cases compared to picking 'B'. However, if my opponent knows this, they might exploit me by consistently picking 'B' when I pick 'R' and getting 40$ each time. On the other hand, if I pick 'B' occasionally, it could potentially force my opponent to switch strategies, leading to situations where I get 45$.

In a one-time game, it would be rational to always pick 'R'. But in this repeated game, things are less clear. If I can convince myself that my opponent is also not overly reckless or cautious, we might both adopt a mixed strategy, picking either 'R' or 'B' randomly. This could lead to more balanced payoffs, but it would require knowing something about the behavior of the anonymous player, which I don't.

Given that this is an experiment and I don't have any information about my opponent, I might choose 'R' as a starting strategy, but be ready to adjust based on the outcomes of the first few rounds. {R}
